<DATE>
<P>
December 10, 1990, Monday, Southland Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 20; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
130 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
OAKLAND; 
</P>
<P>
PIT BULL GIVEN UP, MAIL IS RESTORED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Postal Service plans to seek damages from the owner of a pit bull 
described as "a canine crocodile" that attacked a mail carrier. Postal 
spokesman Dan Demiglio said that because the dog's owner, identified by humane 
officers as Carlos Jackson, turned the dog in, mail will again be delivered to 
the two-block area near Mills College. 
</P>
<P>
Mail deliveries to the neighborhood stopped after the attack on carrier Cecil 
Ivey. Demiglio had warned after the attack that mail would be withheld until 
the dog was taken out of circulation. A neighborhood resident, Shirley Bryant, 
said the dog was well known and feared in the area. The muscular pit bull 
seized Ivey, 45, by the lower right arm during his rounds, inflicting what a 
hospital spokesman called serious wounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
